## 5. Risks and Assumptions

### 5.1 Risks

| Risk | Impact | Likelihood | Mitigation |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| ID format changes in future Kiro Q API versions | Medium | Low | Implement ID passthrough without format assumptions |
| Multiple concurrent tool calls may have race conditions on history storage | High | Medium | Ensure thread-safe history access with proper locking |
| Fix may break other providers that rely on different ID generation logic | Medium | Low | Scope fix to Anthropic converter only, add regression tests |

### 5.2 Assumptions

* The Kiro Q API always provides a stable, unique tool\_use\_id in its responses
* The VS Code extension correctly passes back the tool\_use\_id it received from the streaming response
* The current workaround (disabling tool calling) is acceptable until the fix is deployed
* No other components between kiro-ts and the extension modify the tool\_use\_id

## 6. Non-Functional Requirements

| Category | Requirement | Details |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Performance | No additional latency | The fix must not introduce measurable latency to the streaming response pipeline |
| Reliability | 100% ID consistency | tool\_use\_id must be consistent in every single invocation — no intermittent failures |
| Observability | Debug logging | Add trace-level logging for tool\_use\_id at each transformation point |
| Backward Compatibility | No breaking changes | Fix must not change the streaming response format or extension API contract |

